\significancestatement{Tree mortality is a fundamental demographic process affecting forest dynamics and carbon cycling. Here, for the first time, we use observed survival records over a 15 year period from more than 180,000 individuals, to simultaneously estimate growth-dependent and growth-independent (i.e. stochastic) mortality across 203 tropical forest tree species. We found that growth-dependent mortality was the predominate factor influencing tree mortality rates at Barro Colorado Island. Furthermore, we found that wood density most strongly influenced mortality rates by decreasing growth-independent mortality. However, wood density only accounted for a small fraction of the overall species variability observed in growth-independent mortality rates, suggesting that there must be other species traits that strongly affect mortality. Which traits remains unknown.}

