Here, we attempt to reconcile intra- and inter-specific factors as well as partition instantaneous mortality rates into growth-dependent and growth-independent rates. We achieve this by evaluating the following, unified hazard function, incorporating individual-, species-, and census-level effects:
\begin{equation} \label{eq:model}
\lambda_{i}(t) = \bigg(\overbrace{\gamma_{s[i]}}^{\text{Growth independent}} + \overbrace{\alpha_{s[i]} \, \textrm{e}^{-\beta_{s[i]} \, X_i(t)}}^{\text{Growth dependent}}\bigg) \times \overbrace{\delta_{t}}^{\text{Census}}.
\end{equation}
Eq. \ref{eq:model} allows for additive growth-independent and growth-dependent effects, includes a negative exponential effect of growth rate, and allows for mortality to vary temporally among censuses, via the random effect $\delta_{t}$. Further, the parameters $\alpha_s$, $\beta_s$ and $\gamma_s$ are allowed to vary by species. Here we include an effect of a species trait (wood density, $\rho$), as well as a species random effect that captures any additional species-level differences not represented $\rho$ (for details see Methods).

To validate this model, we fit a series of models with increasing complexity (eq. \ref{eq:model} being the most complex) and compare their skill in predicting patterns of tropical tree mortality for \Sexpr{n_inds(BCI_model_dataset_true_unique)} individuals from \Sexpr{n_spp(BCI_model_dataset_true_unique)} tree species at Barro Colorado Island (BCI), Panama (Fig. \ref{fig1}). The data are repeat censuses of stem diameter and tree status (alive vs. dead) taken over a 15 yr period (Fig. \ref{fig1}A). We compare the skill of different hazard functions in predicting outcomes in novel data (i.e. not used in model calibration) via 10-fold cross-validation (Fig. \ref{fig1}D) \cite{Hooten:2015, Stone:1997tg}. Evaluating models in this way is computationally expensive, making it impossible to run all possible model formulations. We therefore fit models across five stages of model development. At each stage, the best model from the previous stage was taken as input for the next stage.

In stage 1 we ask whether mortality rates vary substantially between censuses, to establish whether a census effect is required. The null model is simply a constant, invariant with respect to species, growth rate, or year.
In stage 2 we ask whether a hazard function including both growth-dependent and independent terms outperforms a function including only one of these? Species effects were excluded, so we are simply asking which of three functional forms for $\lambda_i(t)$ (Fig. \ref{fig1}B) best represents the data. The simplest form (Fig. \ref{fig1}B, left) assumes a constant (growth-independent) hazard rate. The second form (Fig. \ref{fig1}B, middle) assumes the risk of dying declines towards an asymptote of zero as growth increases. The third form (eq. Fig. \ref{fig1}B, right) is the summation of the two previous models; this allows $\lambda_i(t)$ to decrease exponentially with increasing growth rate, but, unlike B, asymptoting at some baseline rate $\textgreater 0$. Combined, these three models capture a variety of functional responses previously proposed, including effects represented in current vegetation models \cite{Moorcroft:2001ws,McDowell:2011dr}, which have not previously been systematically compared. We also investigate which growth measure (stem diameter or stem area increment) more skilfully predicts growth-dependent mortality.
In stage 3, we examined whether including wood density (a species-level trait) improved model skill, and if so, whether the effect of wood density was on growth-dependent or growth-independent hazard, or both? Finally, we fit a model that allowed parameters to vary by species-level effects not captured by wood density. This allowed us to ask what proportion of inter-specific hazard variability is explained by wood density. Using the final `best' model we also conducted some posthoc tests, to determine how species-level parameters were associated with their maximum size and light requirement.

\section*{Results}

\subsection*{Mortality over time}
Comparing the three 5-year intervals between censuses from 1995 to 2010, we found tree mortality progressively decreasing over time. The highest proportion of trees death occurred between 1995\textendash 2000 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_model_dataset_true_unique, 1)}\%) followed by 2000\textendash 2005 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_model_dataset_true_unique, 2)}\%) and 2005\textendash 2010 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_model_dataset_true_unique, 3)}\%). Consequently, when we allowed hazard rates to be scaled by census (i.e. adding term $\delta$) we observed a significant increase in predictive skill (Fig. \ref{fig2}A). Assuming the long-term average census effect ($\delta$) is 1, deaths were \Sexpr{census_effects(final_model,1)}\% higher in 1995\textendash 2000, and \Sexpr{census_effects(final_model,2)}\% and \Sexpr{census_effects(final_model,3)}\% lower in 2000\textendash 2005 and 2005\textendash 2010, respectively.

