\subsection*{Effect of wood density on mortality rates}
Including wood density as an effect on either growth-independent or growth-dependent parameters significantly improved model skill, relative to a model without such effects (Fig. \ref{fig2} A,B). The most parsimonious model, with highest predictive skill, was that attributing the wood density effect to the growth-independent hazard term ($\gamma$; Fig. \ref{fig2} B). Thus wood density was correlated with a species' growth-independent mortality rate (Fig. \ref{fig3}).

% This meant that fast growing individuals from a low wood density species had on higher average mortality rates (Fig. \ref{fig4} A,B), and thus higher annual probability of death (Fig. \ref{fig4} C,D), relative to fast growing individuals of high wood density species.

\subsection*{Proportion of variation explained}
By partitioning the modelled variation between our two random effects (i.e. species and census; Fig. \ref{fig5}A), we found that approximately \Sexpr{extract_prop_explained(param_variance_explained, I('species'))}\% of variation in predicted mortality rates was due to species differences, only \Sexpr{extract_prop_explained(param_variance_explained, I('wood_density'))}\% of which was captured by wood density. By contrast, census effects accounted for approximately \Sexpr{extract_prop_explained(param_variance_explained, I('census'))}\% of the total predicted variation in mortality rates. When we partitioned modelled variation into the two independent hazards we found that the growth-dependent hazard (i.e. the part of the model allowed to vary by individual growth) accounted for \Sexpr{extract_prop_explained(param_variance_explained, I('growth_dependent'))}\% of the overall variation in mortality rates, and the remainder was attributed to the growth-independent hazard.

\subsection*{Mortality rates, maximum species size and species light requirements}
We found that $\alpha$, the effect of low growth rate, and $\gamma$, the growth-independent hazard term, were weakly and positively correlated with gap index, a measure of species light requirement (Fig. \ref{fig6} A,C, E). By contrast, $\beta$ (the exponential decay with increasing growth rate) was negatively correlated gap index. The combination of these correlations suggest that species which predominately recruit in gaps (i.e. higher gap index) were more prone to death due to both low growth and stochastic chance. They also required faster growth rates to achieve a given mortality rate relative to a species that recruits in non-gaps. We detected no strong correlations between estimated species parameters and their associated maximum DBH (Fig. \ref{fig6} B,D,F,H).


